<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18360201-545">
               <interp inst="t18360201-545" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18360201"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18360201-545" type="date" value="18360201"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18360201-545-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-545-18360201 t18360201-545-offence-1 t18360201-545-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>545. <persName id="def1-545-18360201" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-545-18360201" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-545-18360201" type="age" value="19"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-545-18360201" type="surname" value="WILKINSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-545-18360201" type="given" value="WILLIAM WALTON"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM WALTON WILKINSON</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18360201-545-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18360201-545-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18360201-545-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp>for stealing, on the <rs id="t18360201-cd-124" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360201-545-offence-1 t18360201-cd-124"></join>29th of January</rs>, 5 half-crowns, the monies of <persName id="t18360201-name-939" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-939" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-939" type="surname" value="NEEDHAM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-939" type="given" value="RALPH"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360201-545-offence-1 t18360201-name-939"></join>Ralph Needham</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360201-name-940" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-940" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-940" type="surname" value="NEEDHAM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-940" type="given" value="RALPH"></interp>RALPH NEEDHAM</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a linen-draper, and live in Shoreditch. The prisoner was my shopman—I had some suspicion, and marked half-crowns, shillings, and sixpences, to the amount of 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—on the 29th of January and put them in ht till, about nine o'clock—I then went upon a lead-flat, where there is a sky-light, through which I could see into the shop—I saw the prisoner go round the counter, pull the till out and put his hand in what he took out I cannot tell—I came down, and counted the money and found one half-crown short—I sent for a policeman, and gave the pri<lb></lb>soner in charge—this half-crown is mine—it is marked with a cross behind the head.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DOANE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Where were they taken from? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Four were found in his box—three of them were marked—this is one that was in the till that night—I missed this half-crown.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Can you take upon yourself to swear positively that there have not been shillings and sixpence to an equivalent amount put into your till? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I can; the other four half-crowns I had not missed, but I can swear to these being mine—three of them are marked with my initials behind the head—I know the prisoner had a particular fancy for half-crowns.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360201-name-941" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-941" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-941" type="surname" value="SEAL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-941" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS SEAL</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police constable G</hi> 16) I took the prisoner into cus<lb></lb>tody—I took him to the station and received from him the key of his box—I went and found in it forty half-crowns, one of which was marked and Mr. Needham identified it as his—they were sealed up in a white paper—I searched further and in another part of the box I found in a leathern purse 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in half-crows, three amongst which were marked—the prisoner declared that all he had taken was 17<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., all in half-crowns.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360201-name-942" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-942" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-942" type="surname" value="COSS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-942" type="given" value="WILLIAM BROOM"></interp>WILLIAM BROOM COSS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable G</hi> 217) I was called in to take the prisoner—I found on him this half-crown—I then went with Seal, and found this other money in his box.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183602010164"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence</hi>. The object I had in view in keeping half-crowns was this: I had some gold once when I received my wages—I gave away half-a-sovereign for a six pence and I said I would never keep gold any more.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360201-name-943" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-943" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-943" type="surname" value="WILKINSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-943" type="given" value="JANE"></interp>JANE WILKINSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the prisoner's sister. I recollect his having 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. in sovereigns paid him by his master four or five months ago—he came to me and my mother to h ave them changed for half-crowns, he said they looked so much more than sovereigns.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MRS. WILKINSONS</hi>. I have heard what my daughter has said; it is per<lb></lb>fectly correct-within the last two years I have changed as many as ten sovereigns for half-crowns for the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360201-name-944" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-944" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-944" type="surname" value="WILLIAMS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-944" type="given" value="WM"></interp>WM. WILLIAMS</persName>
                  </hi>. I was fellow-shopman with the prisoner—I know he had a fancy for having money changed for half-crowns—he knew the money in the till was market on the Wednesday previous to his being taken up.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How came he to know it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He told me it was marked and asked the reason why—he has to go to the till to get change—I told him that I thought it was very strange Mr. Needham suspected us—I told my master that the prisoner had noticed that the money was marked.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360201-name-945" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-945" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-945" type="surname" value="NEEDHAM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-945" type="given" value="RALPH"></interp>RALPH NEEDHAM</persName>
                  </hi> re-examined. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you marked any money on the Wednesday? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> That with my initials on it was marked on the Tues<lb></lb>day and Wednesday, but that with a cross on Friday the 29th.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DOANE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> And some with each of the marks were found in the pri<lb></lb>soner's possession? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, I has marked shillings and sixpences, but no marked shillings were found in his box—I only missed one half-crown on the Friday—it is impossible that he could have substituted any other money for that one as I saw him go to the till, and I came down directly, and there was only 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 17<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. there—I had put 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. there—he was taken immediately after I had seen him go to the hill—he had not had time to go up to his box.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY. Q</hi>. When did you pay him his wages? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have not paid him any thing, he had not been with me more than eight or nine weeks. (Mr. Roberts, a linen-draper, of Oxford-street; and Mr. Kenny, a linen<lb></lb>draper, of the Kent-road; gave the prisoner a good character.)</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18360201-545-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18360201-545-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18360201-545-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="withRecommendation"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">GUILTY</hi>. Aged 19—Recommended to mercy by the Jury and Prosecutor.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
